Love this place. My first time there was for jazz night - a rotating cast of extremely talented players just shredding song after song. I was incredulous when someone asked if I wanted to jam. I play a little jazz, but being nowhere near the level of these players, I declined, content to just listen. Great ambiance, intimate setting, I keep coming back for more.

This lowkey spot is home to friendly bartenders, delicious mystery punch, and the best fortnightly DJ dance party this side of Lake Michigan. Let your hair down and chill in the cozy but spacious bar area, or enjoy the well-appointed biergarten out back.  Don't call it a patio, though. It's a biergarten.
Bar prices are good for having so much live music for cheap. Wish they had draft beer or some dive bar specials. Somehow both ratty and elegant.

Just the best! Live music and entertainment, no nonsense

This place is kind of the true epitome of cool intellectualism in Chicago. With comedy nights infused with local musicians to experimental jazz nights, you'll never be in want of something Avant guarde. No beers on tap and (I think) cash only, you'll find a small but excellent choice of spirits and at least some good candidate and bottles. The beer garden is nice and cozy, but closes at 11 because it's in a neighborhood. The bartender is also always super nice and willing to talk if your sporting solo.
What a fun little spot! We loved our date night here. Great music, casual crowd. Will come back!

Although it has changed over the years, the Brain remains one of my personal favorite bars in Chicago. It's intimate, has a great jukebox, and now that it's affiliated with Constellation, there's excellent live music and arts events there on a regular basis. Great selection of beer too.

Walked in here on a Saturday night around 10. Cute little bar and live venue, it didn't start to get rowdy until around 11 p.m. The inside is very clean, non-divey, 60s retro theme (think Mad Men) w/ strong cocktails to match -- $9 cocktails. One of the more affordable deals on mixed drinks I've run into in the city. I didn't try the arcade games, but a great place to get a buzz going/dance if you're in the neighborhood.

While it's lost a tad bit of its original charm since being spiffied up since reopening, this is still one of the premier spaces to hear great music and discussions in Chicago. Focusing on jazz and local musicians, I've never been disappointed in the performances here, even when coming in on a random night not knowing ahead of time who will be on stage. The bar staff is always top notch and interesting to talk with, and the affordable - and impressive - beer list makes up for it being cash only. Come to a show, then stick around and strike up a conversation. You won't be disappointed.
Best bar north of Madison!

It's an institution. It's been around forever. And they have great literary readings there which is really cool.  The drinks are cheap and the bartender, Dan is great. Super friendly and nice.  Give it a shot!

It feels a bit DIY, but nothing feels especially rushed or thoughtless. The seating is really well placed,  the staff is friendly, and all of the spaces flow together nicely

Love this place; perhaps my favorite hangout in the city, plus its local. Very low, ambient lighting. Classic Galaga arcade game (among others). Great beer selection, but best of all the BEST jukebox in the city constantly being updated.

This is like a magic land bar.  Kitschy and fun, there are plenty of seating areas and a great variety of brews. Love the mood lighting as well. It's hard to go wrong here, considering they pride themselves on being a hub of art and community.  By the time you walk out, you'll already be thinking about the next time you can come back. It's that good.

This bar was oozing with potential, but somehow it didn't seem to gel. The bartender was helpful. She gave me great recommendations of other places around town to check out and exchanged my five for ones with a smile.  The ambiance was comfortable with eclectic knick knacks placed here and there, Pacman and other early 80's arcade games, and a superb juke box. I played Gnarls Barkley, James Brown, and Art Brut. However, no one seemed affected by the music.  The people in the bar seemed somewhat disconnected. The sets of friends talking about the bad dating scene and other random mishaps didn't even acknowledge the other couples with the same conversations. I like communal bars where everyone is friendly to each other. I didn't get this here at all.  I ended up leaving after two drinks and 10 games of Pacman. I would give Hungry Brain another chance, maybe during another trip to Chicago, but not on a Wednesday night.
